    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm working on a linear regression model for some housing price data, but I've run into a snag. When I check my residuals, they're definitely not normally distributed—there's some really weird skew and some significant outliers messing with the fit. What's the best way to handle this so I don't violate the Gauss-Markov assumptions?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Since your residuals are non-normal with skew and outliers, violating the normality assumption for inference is a concern. Consider transforming your dependent variable (housing price) using a log or square root transformation to reduce skewness. Alternatively, you can use robust regression methods, like Huber or RANSAC, which are less sensitive to outliers than Ordinary Least Squares (OLS). Remember that while strict normality is needed for hypothesis testing, OLS estimates are still unbiased even if residuals aren't perfectly normal.",
      "source": "target",
