    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I think I'll try a log transformation first. But what if the outliers aren't just skewed values, but actual errors or weird edge cases in the data that don't follow the general trend at all? Like, if they are totally unpredictable and just breaking the distribution pattern, how do I distinguish between a legitimate extreme value and something that shouldn't even be in the model?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Distinguishing genuine anomalies from legitimate extremes requires domain knowledge and statistical investigation. First, plot your data using box plots or scatter plots to visualize the magnitude of the outliers compared to your typical data points. If the outlier deviates wildly from the established pattern, it might be a data entry error or an irrelevant observation. In such cases, cautiously removing or winsorizing these extreme points can lead to a more accurate model fit based on the core data structure.",
      "source": "target",
